ial and non-territorial powers. Katzenstein argues that globalization and internationalization create open or porous regions. Regions may provide solutions to the contradictions between states and markets, security and insecurity, nationalism and cosmopolitanism. Embedded in the American imperium, regions are now central to world politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aInternational relations. 0aRegionalismxPolitical aspects. 0aWorld politicsy1945-1989. 0aWorld politicsy1989-. 4aAsian Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170038540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501700385423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501700385/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK